 is embodied by the ambiguous figure of the parasite, a stock character of Greek comic drama. The book interrogates three separate sites where political actors have used humour ‘parasitically’ in order to make political claims and demands. In so doing, it not only outlines humour’s political potential and limitations, but also demonstrates how everyday practices can draw from, feed into, interrupt, and potentially transform global-political relations.Representing the first monograph-length study on the politics of humour within International Relations, this book makes a timely contribution to debates about the politics of humour, subjectivity and everyday life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aInternational relationsxPhilosophy. 0aPolitical satirexHistory and criticism. 0aWit and humorxPhilosophy. 0aWit and humorxPolitical aspects. 4aPolitical Studies 2022. 7aHUMOR / Topic / Political.2bisacsh  aHIV/AIDS.  aHolocaust.  aInternational Relations.  acomedy.  aeveryday.  ahumour.  aparasite.  apolitics.  aresistance.  asubjectivity.1 aWedderburn, Alister, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198840uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615070740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526150707423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526150707/original  a978-3-11-128198-8  Manchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packageb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles